.TH PRT-UPDATE 8 "prt-#VERSION# Manual"
.SH NAME
prt-update \- Update packages in the listed order
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B prt update
.B [-v|-vv]
.B [--test]
.B [--log]
.B [--deps]
.B [--group]
.BI [--margs=' PKGMK_ARGS '| PKGMK_ALIASES ]
.BI [--aargs=' PKGADD_ARGS '| PKGADD_ALIASES ]
.BI [--ignore= PORT1,PORT2,... ]
.B [--install-scripts|[--pre-install][--post-install]]
.I PORT1 PORT2 ...
.SH DESCRIPTION
Update all packages in the listed order.
.br
Note that you can do this from any directory.
It looks in all directories specified in \fC/etc/prt.conf\fR.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-v
Be more verbose.
.TP
.B \-vv
Log to stdout the updating process.
.TP
.B \-\-test
Dry run, don't actually update anything.
.TP
.B \-\-log
Create a transaction log file. It can be set globally for all
transactions (see "writelog" in prt.conf(5)).
.TP
.B \-\-deps
Update all packages in the listed order including their new dependencies.
.TP
.B \-\-group
Update all packages in the listed order, but stop if updating of
one package fails. This can be used to update packages where package2
depends on package1.
.TP
.BI \-\-margs=' PKGMK_ARGS '
Arguments to be passed to pkgmk(8).
.TP
.BI PKGMK_ALIASES
.I \-fr
Force rebuild, implies 'pkgmk -f'; same as --margs=-f
.br
.I \-um
Update md5sum, implies 'pkgmk -um'; same as --margs=-um
.br
.I \-im
Ignore md5sum, implies 'pkgmk -im'; same as --margs=-im
.br
.I \-us
Update signature, implies 'pkgmk -us'; same as --margs=-us
.br
.I \-is
Ignore signature, implies 'pkgmk -is'; same as --margs=-is
.br
.I \-uf
Update footprint, implies 'pkgmk -uf'; same as --margs=-uf
.br
.I \-if
Ignore footprint, implies 'pkgmk -if'; same as --margs=-if
.br
.I \-ns
No stripping, implies 'pkgmk -ns'; same as --margs=-ns
.br
.I \-kw
Keep working directory, implies 'pkgmk -kw'; same as --margs=-kw
.TP
.BI \-\-aargs=' PKGADD_ARGS '
Arguments to be passed to pkgadd(8).
.TP
.BI PKGADD_ALIASES
.I \-f, \-i
Force install. Implies 'pkgadd --f'; same as --aargs=-f
.TP
.BI \-\-ignore=' PORT1,PORT2,... '
Don't install/update those packages, even if they're listed as
dependency.
.TP
.B \-\-install\-scripts
Execute pre-install and post-install script if they're there.
.TP
.B \-\-pre\-install
Execute pre-install script if it's there.
.TP
.B \-\-post\-install
Execute post-install scripts if it's there.
